text.tspan: The Wriggle Down
The scene opens with the sound of a small child crying. Rain batters the near by
window and our protagonist wonders why such a pretty storm is marred by the
obnoxious cries of a spoiled child. See he knew this was Tommy from apartment six
throwing a tantrum. Given the proximity to supper it's a good bet he doesn't want to
finish some vegetable or his behavior has had some dessert taken away. For a
moment things quieten and his mind slips away to being in a cabin rather than a slum
apartment surrounded by functioning alcoholics and bratty children...and then as if on
queue the Harpers in apartment twelve can be heard stomping around and screaming
at each other. "Perhaps it's time to dust off the umbrella and head to a near by park
bench for a while" he thinks as he finishes his now cold coffee.
Digging through his closet he finds the seldom used umbrella. Before closing the door
he grabs a light jacket, not waterproof but the best choice he has. He slips on his
shoes, pockets his keys and opens his front door to the musty hall. The building reeks
of decades of blue collar alcoholics, burnt suppers and various smoke odors. It was a
harsh reminder of why he was stepping out for a walk in the rain. Everyone wants to
trade up in life but most have to suffice with small moments of improvement. Like a
light rain and park air. Not fresh given the cities traffic but an improvement from the
musty apartment building. He shuts and locks the door behind himself and quickly
moves to the front door. As quick as he can open-close, hop down the stoop, pop the
umbrella and down the street for a much need reprieve to the day.
